9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 664, L.D. 1669, “An Act to Establish the
10 Cannabis Advisory Council”
11 Amend the bill by striking out all of section 3 and inserting the following:
12 'Sec. 3. 28-B MRSA §115 is enacted to read:
13 §115. Cannabis Advisory Council
14 1. Appointment; composition. The Cannabis Advisory Council, referred to in this
15 section as "the council" and established by Title 5, section 12004-I, subsection 2-J, consists
16 of 12 members who are appointed as follows:
17 A. Two members who are registrants under the Maine Medical Use of Cannabis Act,
18 who are not also licensees under the Cannabis Legalization Act, of which at least one
19 member is a registered caregiver who cultivates cannabis for medical use outdoors,
20 appointed by the President of the Senate. In making the appointments under this
21 paragraph, the President of the Senate shall consider up to 6 recommendations from
22 associations representing the interests of registrants under the Maine Medical Use of
23 Cannabis Act;
24 B. Two members who are licensees under the Cannabis Legalization Act, who are not
25 also registrants under the Maine Medical Use of Cannabis Act, of which at least one
26 member has a cultivation facility license, appointed by the Speaker of the House. In
27 making the appointments under this paragraph, the Speaker of the House shall consider
28 up to 6 recommendations from associations representing the interests of the adult use
29 cannabis industry;
30 C. Two members who are registrants and licensees under both the Maine Medical Use
31 of Cannabis Act and the Cannabis Legalization Act, of which at least one member has
32 a manufacturing facility registration certificate or license, appointed jointly by the
33 President of the Senate and the Speaker of the House. In making the appointments
34 under this paragraph, the President of the Senate and the Speaker of the House shall
35 consider up to 6 recommendations from associations representing the interests of the
36 cannabis industry;
Page 1 - 132LR1196(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 664, L.D. 1669
1 D. One public member who is not a registrant under the Maine Medical Use of
2 Cannabis Act, a licensee under the Cannabis Legalization Act or a lobbyist or lobbyist
3 associate as defined in Title 3, section 312-A, subsections 10 and 10-A, respectively,
4 and who has knowledge of and interest in cannabis, appointed by the Speaker of the
5 House;
6 E. Two members who are municipal officials in municipalities that have ordinances
7 allowing for all registration types under the Maine Medical Use of Cannabis Act and
8 all license types under the Cannabis Legalization Act, appointed by the director;
9 F. Two members who have a demonstrated knowledge of cannabis science, medicine
10 or research and, at a minimum, a bachelor's degree, appointed by the director. The
11 director shall make a reasonable effort to appoint a member who has at least 5 years of
12 relevant experience; and
13 G. One member who is a public health professional, appointed by the director.
14 To the extent practicable, the membership of the council must reflect a geographic
15 distribution across the State.
16 2. Cannabis business advocate. The cannabis business advocate established by
17 Public Law 2023, chapter 683 serves as an ex officio nonvoting member of the council.
18 3. Purpose. The council shall make recommendations to the director and the joint
19 standing committee of the Legislature having jurisdiction over cannabis matters
20 concerning:
21 A. How best to work with state agencies, municipal governments, the medical use
22 cannabis industry and adult use cannabis industry and citizen groups to make
23 improvements to and maintain the quality of the State's medical use cannabis industry
24 and adult use cannabis industry; and
25 B. Matters of interest to the State's medical use cannabis industry and adult use
26 cannabis industry, including, but not limited to, financial services, taxation, cannabis-
27 related research and development, environmental and public health protection,
28 cannabis policy in other states and federal legalization.
29 The council is responsible for bringing forward to the director and the joint standing
30 committee of the Legislature having jurisdiction over cannabis matters issues of concern
31 to the cannabis industry and for assisting in the dissemination of information to members
32 of the cannabis industry. The council may solicit and consider public comment during its
33 meetings.
34 4. Terms. The term of a member appointed to the council is 3 years, except that a
35 vacancy during an unexpired term must be filled in the same manner as for the original
36 member for the unexpired portion of the member's term. A member may not serve more
37 than 2 consecutive terms.
38 5. Chair and vice-chair. The council shall elect a member of the council as chair and
39 a member as vice-chair at the first regular meeting of each year. The term of the chair and
40 vice-chair is one year.
41 6. Meetings; staffing. The council shall meet at least 4 times a year and, to the extent
42 practicable, at more than one location throughout the State. It may also meet at other times
