COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 664, L.D. 1669
1 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
2 number to read consecutively.
3 SUMMARY
44 This amendment increases the total membership of the Cannabis Advisory Council
55 established in the bill from 10 members to 12 members. It also adjusts the membership of
66 the council in the following ways.
7 1. It decreases from 3 to 2 the members who are registrants under the Maine Medical
8 Use of Cannabis Act and specifies that the one member who must be a registered caregiver
9 must cultivate cannabis for medical use outdoors. It also clarifies that these members may
10 not also be licensees under the Cannabis Legalization Act.
11 2. It removes a public member who is a qualifying patient under the Maine Medical
12 Use of Cannabis Act with knowledge of and interest in the medical use of cannabis.
13 3. It decreases from 3 to 2 the members who are licensees under the Cannabis
14 Legalization Act and clarifies that these members may not also be registrants under the
15 Maine Medical Use of Cannabis Act.
16 4. It adds 2 members who are registrants and licensees under both the Maine Medical
17 Use of Cannabis Act and the Cannabis Legalization Act. These members will be appointed
18 jointly by the President of the Senate and the Speaker of the House, based upon 6
19 recommendations from associations representing the interests of the cannabis industry.
20 5. It clarifies that the public member with knowledge of and interest in cannabis may
21 not also be a registrant or licensee under the Maine Medical Use of Cannabis Act or the
22 Cannabis Legalization Act or a lobbyist or lobbyist associate.
23 6. It increases from one to 2 the members who are municipal officials in municipalities
24 that have ordinances allowing for all registration types under the Maine Medical Use of
25 Cannabis Act and all license types under the Cannabis Legalization Act.
26 7. It increases from one to 2 the members who have a demonstrated knowledge of
27 cannabis science and research and broadens the criteria to include medicine.
28 8. It adds one member who is a public health professional, to be appointed by the
29 Director of the Office of Cannabis Policy within the Department of Administrative and
30 Financial Services.
31 9. It adds the cannabis business advocate as an ex officio nonvoting member of the
32 council.
33 It also provides for staggered initial terms for members of the council.
34 The amendment also changes the purpose of the council to remove making
35 recommendations on changing the tracking system contract and including making
36 recommendations on matters of interest to the cannabis industry related to financial
37 services, taxation, cannabis-related research and development, environmental health
38 protection and cannabis policy in other states. It also provides that the council may solicit
39 and consider public comment during its meetings and that the office must provide
40 administrative and staff support for the council within existing resources.
Page 4 - 132LR1196(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 664, L.D. 1669
1 The amendment also increases the number of times the council must meet from at least
2 once a year to at least 4 times a year and includes a requirement that, to the extent
3 practicable, the council must meet at more than one location throughout the State. It also
4 removes the provisions specific to a meeting with an organization holding the contract for
5 the tracking system for cannabis with the State.
